<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-689-960  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 689 960.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  July 31 1990 v4 n26 p125(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple earnings up in Q3, but Q4 looks flat. (third and fourthquarters)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pfiffner, Pamela.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>For the 3rd qtr of FY 1990, ending June 29, 1990, Apple postedrevenue of $1.37 billion, up 9 percent from $1.25 billion for 3rdqtr 1989.andP;  Over the same period, earnings per share rose 30percent from 74 cents to 96 cents, and net income climbed 25percent from $96.1 million to $119.8 million.andP;  International salesrose from 39 percent of total sales in 3rd qtr 1989 to 42 percentin 3rd qtr 1990.andP;  Apple stock dropped $2.875 to $41.75 on July 19,the day after 3rd qtr results were announced.andP;  The Apple boardapproved the repurchase of 5 million shares after the 3rd qtrresults were announced.andP;  Apple Chmn and CEO John Sculley warnedinvestors not to expect 4th qtr results to match those of 1989,when Apple posted revenue of $1.38 billion and net income of $161million, or $1.24 per share.andP;  Sculley blamed the biggest producttransition in Apple's history and slow sales in anticipation ofApple's Oct 1990 Macintosh rollouts for the pessimisticprojection.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (earnings).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     Computer IndustryProfitForecastingThird QuarterFourth QuarterRevenue.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Apple posts 3rd-quarter gain. (graph)Person:    Sculley, John (forecasts).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Pamela PfiffnerandM;Cupertino, Calif.andP;  -- Apple this month reported third-quarter results thatwere in line with its projections, but its warnings about the fourth-quarteroutlook left analysts cautious and some investors jittery.andM;For the quarter ending June 29, Apple posted revenues of $1.37 billion, up 9percent from $1.25 billion for the same period last year.andP;  Net income rose 25percent to $119.8 million compared with $96.1 million last year.andP;  Earningswere 96 cents per share, up 30 percent from 74 cents for the same period lastyear.andM;International sales continued to grow, accounting for 42 percent of salescompared with 39 percent in the third quarter of 1989.andM;Apple's results were announced after the market closed July 18.andP;  Apple'sshares dropped $2.875 to $41.75 the following day and hovered in the samerange during the following week.andM;After the results were posted, Apple's board of directors authorized therepurchase of another 5 million shares of Apple common stock.andP;  Apple hasrepurchased 25 million shares of stock since July 1986.andP;  The board alsodeclared a quarterly dividend of 11 cents per share.andM;In a prepared statement, Apple Chairman and CEO John Sculley said, &quot;Overall,we are pleased with these results.&quot; He cited &quot;significant improvements in ourgross margins,&quot; strong sales of higher-end, modular Macs and the success ofrecent &quot;pricing actions&quot; in stimulating demand for some compact models.andM;But Sculley warned investors not to expect too much for the remainder of thefiscal year.andP;  &quot;As we have been indicating for some time, in the final quarterof this year we foresee considerable challenges,&quot; Sculley said.andP;  &quot;We believeit will be difficult to meet the operating results we achieved in the fourthquarter of last year.&quot;andM;Apple posted a net income of $161 million, or $1.24 per share, on revenues of$1.38 billion in its fourth quarter last year.andM;&quot;We continue to be optimistic about our new product plans, which remain onschedule, but we maintain our cautious outlook in the short term about thelevel of demand in our U.S.andP;  market,&quot; Sculley added.andP;  Apple is expected toannounce at least two new lower-cost Macs in October, after the end of itscurrent fiscal year on Sept.andP;  30.andM;In a conference call to analysts on July 18, Sculley said that Apple wasgoing through the biggest product transition in the company's history.andP;  Healso said that widespread publicity about the new October Macs has thepotential of slowing down sales.andM;Following Apple's announcement, Michele Preston, a partner with Cowen andamp; Co.andO;in New York, lowered her estimates for the company's fourth-quarter earningsper share from $1.05 to 69 cents.andP;  On June 28, Preston had recommended Applestock as a buy.andP;  She said she continues to recommend it because there is anopportunity for a rebound with the new Macs.andM;John Dean, an analyst at Salomon Brothers Inc. in San Francisco, agreed.andO;&quot;There may be a pent-up demand for Apple products, and the new Macs will beout in time for the Christmas season and in time for fiscal year-endpurchases for a lot of companies.&quot;andM;Still, he cautioned, &quot;There are things in the short term that will improverevenues, but what about long-term solutions?andP;  We need to see more of Apple'sstrategic direction.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>